                .column.is-8.is-offset-1-desktop
                    .case-study__intro-text-wrapper
                        %p.case-study__introduction
                            The Puerto Rico Open is the only PGA Tour event held on the island of Puerto Rico, and one of the few in the entire Caribbean. First played in 2008, it has grown into a 17-year fixture on the island's sporting and cultural calendar, hosted at Grand Reserve Golf Club in Río Grande.
                        %p.case-study__introduction
                            Beyond the competition, the PR Open functions as a significant economic and community institution: the 2025 edition was projected to inject $5.5 million into the local economy, generate over $700,000 in tax revenue, support 1,000 direct and indirect jobs, and book more than 2,500 hotel nights.
                        %p.case-study__introduction
                            The event markets itself under the tagline "Open for everyone," anchored by "El 19," an on-site food, bar, and music hub designed to make the tournament accessible to a broader local audience beyond traditional golf fans.
                        %p.case-study__introduction
                            To match the scale and cultural significance of the event, the website was redesigned to serve three distinct audiences at once: local Puerto Rican fans, golf tourists traveling to the island and diaspora fans watching remotely from the mainland. The project focused on creating a bilingual, mobile-first experience that could function as both a destination showcase and a live event hub, balancing the premium expectations of a PGA Tour audience with the warmth and local pride that makes the PR Open unlike any other stop on Tour.
                        %p.case-study__introduction
                            Note: The designs presented in this case study reflect the full website structure and content strategy developed through the research and design process. The final implemented product was adapted to meet client priorities and budget constraints. Some pages, features, and content sections were modified, consolidated, or deferred as a result.
